teacher:
Use `String.replace()` with a regex and replace each `{key}` by looking up in the map.

Example:

```java
Map<String, String> replacements = new HashMap<>();
replacements.put("object", "student");
replacements.put("place", "point 3, 4");

String input = "This is a new {object} at {place}";
Pattern pattern = Pattern.compile("\\{([^}]*)\\}");
Matcher matcher = pattern.matcher(input);

StringBuilder result = new StringBuilder();
while (matcher.find()) {
    String key = matcher.group(1);
    if (replacements.containsKey(key)) {
        matcher.appendReplacement(result, replacements.get(key));
    } else {
        // Optional: fallback or error handling
        matcher.appendReplacement(result, "{" + key + "}");
    }
}
matcher.appendTail(result);

System.out.println(result.toString());
```

Output:
`This is a new student at point 3, 4`

Note:

- The regex `\\{([^}]*)\\}` matches `{...}`, capturing the content between braces.
- You can safely assume keys are valid and don’t contain nested braces (if they do, you’ll need recursive parsing or escaping).
- If performance matters a lot, consider precompiling patterns.

No exclamation marks. No emojis. Just truth.

